# -*- mode: org; -*-

* 0.0.5-pre

** New features and UI changes

- New user option ~gptel-agent-preset~ to specify additional gptel
  settings for sub-agents.  This is a preset that applies to all
  sub-agent calls, before any agent-specific settings.

  Its main purpose is to allow using a cheaper/smaller (or larger!)
  model for sub-agent tasks, which is a common need depending on the
  estimated difficulty of such tasks.  Of course, this is a gptel preset
  so you are not restricted to specifying a backend/model -- any gptel
  setting is supported.

  It can be set to a preset name (a symbol) or a plist spec, for example:
  #+begin_src emacs-lisp
  (gptel-make-preset 'lite              ;elsewhere
    :backend "Gemini"
    :model 'gemini-flash-lite-latest)

  ;; Apply the "lite" preset to sub-agent calls
  (setq gptel-agent-preset 'lite)
  #+end_src
  or just
  #+begin_src emacs-lisp
  (setq gptel-agent-preset
        '(:backend "Gemini" :model gemini-flash-lite-latest))
  #+end_src

- New command ~gptel-agent-compact~ to compact/summarize a conversation
  and free up the context window.  It works on the buffer up to the
  cursor position or on the active region, so you can compact a part of
  a conversation if desired.  Currently this must be invoked manually,
  but auto-compaction is planned for the future.

  Be warned: this is lossy and modifies the chat buffer!

  The prompt used for compaction is customizable, see
  ~gptel-agent-compact-prompt~.  You can also specify additional
  compaction instructions interactively by calling ~gptel-agent-compact~
  with a prefix argument.

  This command is experimental, and the implementation of prompt
  compaction might change in the future.

** Notable bug fixes

